FGT-ao.def: Fish caught by trawling measures the percentage of a country’s fish caught by bottom or pelagic trawling, where a fishing net is pulled through the water behind a boat. This practice is indiscriminate and wasteful and can severely damage marine ecosystems.
FGT-ao.name: Fish caught by Trawling

FSS-ao.def: Fish stock status evaluates the percentage of a country’s total catch that comes from overexploited or collapsed stocks, considering all fish stocks within a country’s EEZs. Because continued and increased stock exploitation leads to smaller catches, this indicator sheds light on the impact of a country’s fishing practices.
FSS-ao.name: Fish Stock Status

RMS-ao.def: Marine Trophic Index (MTI) describes the health of a country’s fishing stock based on expected catch and changes over time. The MTI describes the degree to which a country is depleting species at higher trophic levels and “fishing down the food web.”
RMS-ao.name: Regional Marine Trophic Index

key-ER.FSH.CAPT.MT-ao.def: Capture fisheries production measures the volume of fish catches landed by a country for all commercial, industrial, recreational and subsistence purposes.
key-ER.FSH.CAPT.MT-ao.name: Fishery production, capture and aquaculture (metric tons)
